text: Fans love when there is a film adaption of a bestselling novel like The Longest Ride by renowned author Nicholas Sparks. We devour each chapter and detail. However, when the film writers completely change the foundation of Luke and Sophia's relationship in terms of how they met and how their relationship grew, it pisses off¬†fans like me. I hope Ira's character is incorporated sooner than the trailer shows; he also did not seem as feeble and stubborn as his character is in the book. Scott Eastwood as Luke was a perfect choice! Maybe it is just me, but I always imagined Sophia as a dark haired chick when I read the book, so I wish her character resembled that. I am excited for the movie but also apprehensive if it will be up to the standards of the novel.

text: Alright so I really like the movie. Yes it was cheesy and predictable but I'm a girl so shut the hell up. I did notice though....... That throughout the entire movie neither of them ever said "I love you." Now I don't know if I missed it but the second the movie started I was waiting for that moment and it never happened. I wanted to know if the director or writer or whoever was in charge purposely did that to covey some sort of hidden message... Maybe I'm thinking too much into it because it is 3 am where I live and I haven't slept in around 50 hours but I think they are trying to say that "I love you" can be said in thousands of different ways then the words themselves. For instance; telling someone you'll be anywhere and do anything for them even if u don't want to, and letting them know that they were on your mind all day, or sacrificing your entire life plan for that person. Again, I'm probably just overthinking it but I'd like to hear other's opinions.
author: Hayley D.Lacy
